            <div n="1" xml:lang="eng">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Cataracts of the Orinoco.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;A foaming surface of<lb break="yes"/>four miles in length presents itself
                    at once to the eye:<lb break="yes"/>iron-black masses of rock resembling ruins
                    and battle-<lb break="no"/>mented towers rise frowning from the waters. Rocks<lb
                        break="yes"/>and islands are adorned with the luxuriant vegetation<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the tropical forest; a perpetual mist hangs over the<lb
                        break="yes"/>waters, and the summits of the lofty palms pierce through<lb
                        break="yes"/>the cloud of spray and vapour. When the rays of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>glowing evening sun are refracted in these humid exha-<lb
                        break="no"/>lations a magic optical effect begins. Coloured bows<lb
                        break="yes"/>shine, vanish, and reappear; and the ethereal image is<lb
                        break="yes"/>swayed to and fro by the breath of the sportive breeze.<lb
                        break="yes"/>During the long rainy season the streaming waters bring<lb
                        break="yes"/>down islands of vegetable mould, and thus the naked<lb
                        break="yes"/>rocks are studded with bright flower-beds, adorned with<lb
                        break="yes"/>Melastomas and Droseras, and with small-leaved mimo-<lb
                        break="no"/>sas and ferns. These spots recall to the recollection of<lb
                        break="yes"/>the European those blocks of granite decked with flowers<lb
                        break="yes"/>which rise solitary amidst the glaciers of Savoy, and are<lb
                        break="yes"/>called by the dwellers in the Alps &#x201C;Jardins,&#x201D; or
                        &#x201C;Cour-<lb break="no"/>tills.&#x201D; In the blue distance the eye
                    rests on the moun-<lb break="no"/>tain chain of Cunavami, a long extended ridge
                        which<lb break="yes"/>terminates abruptly in a truncated cone. We saw the<lb
                        break="yes"/>latter (Calitamini is its Indian name) glowing at sunset<lb
                        break="yes"/>as if in roseate flames. This appearance returns daily:<lb
                        break="yes"/>no one has ever been near the mountain to detect the<lb
                        break="yes"/>precise cause of this brightness, which may perhaps<lb
                        break="yes"/>proceed from a reflecting surface produced by the de-<lb
                        break="no"/>composition of talc or mica slate. During the five days<lb
                        break="yes"/>which we passed in the neighbourhood of the cataracts,<lb
                        break="yes"/>it was striking to hear the thunder of the rushing tor-<lb
                        break="no"/>rents sound three times louder by night than by day. In<lb
                        break="yes"/>all European waterfalls the same phenomenon is re-<lb
                        break="no"/>marked. What can be its cause in a wilderness where<lb
                        break="yes"/>there is nothing to interrupt the repose of nature? Per-<lb
                        break="no"/>haps the currents of heated ascending air, by causing<lb
                        break="yes"/>irregular density in the elastic medium, impede the pro-<lb
                        break="no"/>pagation of sound during the day, by the disturbance<lb
                        break="yes"/>they <choice>
                        <sic>[may</sic>
                        <corr type="editorial">may</corr>
                    </choice> occasion in the waves of sound; whereas<lb break="yes"/>during the
                    nocturnal cooling of the earth&#x2019;s surface the<lb break="yes"/>upward
                    currents entirely cease.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">
                        <persName key="humboldt_av">Humboldt</persName>&#x2019;s Aspects of<lb
                            break="yes"/>Nature.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
